value.value: A thyroid gland carcinoma characterized by the presence of cribriform, trabecular, follicular, papillary, and solid growth patterns and squamoid morulae formation. It may occur with familial adenomatous polyposis or sporadically.

label.value: Warthin-Like Variant Thyroid Gland Papillary Carcinoma

value.value: A rare variant of papillary thyroid gland carcinoma characterized by the presence of eosinophilic large cells lining the papillae and a brisk lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate in the papillary stalks.

A collection of gelatinous-appearing grey matter cells in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord that receives direct input from the dorsal nerve roots and plays a role in regulating pain impulses at the spinal cord level.

label.value: Thyroid Gland Papillary Carcinoma with Fibromatosis/Fasciitis-Like/Desmoid-Type Stroma

value.value: A rare morphologic variant of papillary thyroid gland carcinoma characterized by the presence of abundant and cellular stroma resembling nodular fasciitis, fibromatosis, or other proliferative myofibroblastic processes. (WHO)
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of an exuberant proliferation of fibroblasts and myofibroblasts in the stroma of a tumor sample.
A protein encoded by the VEGFA gene.

label.value: Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor A 165 Isoform

value.value: Vascular endothelial growth factor A 165 isoform (191 aa, ~22 kDa) is encoded by the human VEGFA gene. This protein plays a role in the positive regulation of both cell proliferation and angiogenesis.
A family of enzymes involved in cytidine deamination, which converts cytidine into uracil, in DNA or RNA. These enzymes play a role in mRNA editing and retroviral host defenses.

The combination of polymorphisms in the DNA encoding human leukocyte antigens (HLA) and killer-cell immunoglobulin-like receptors (KIR) found in an individual's genome. Certain combinations may indicate that the subject is more likely to develop certain diseases such as autoimmune disorders, viral infections, and cancer.
Any immunoglobulin that recognizes antigens expressed by human papillomaviruses.

Any anaerobic bacteria that metabolizes complex carbohydrates to produce butyrate. These microorganisms may form colonies in the intestines of mammals; their presence may aid the host by catabolizing undigested fiber and starch. Additionally, butyrate is metabolized by colonic epithelial cells and may protect the host against ulcerative colitis and cancer.
Any antibody that recognizes tumor-associated peptide antigens that are in neoantigen peptide-based vaccines.
Long-lived antigen-specific T-lymphocytes, which express CD8 and effector cytokines. Upon subsequent exposure to their target antigen, these cells rapidly become effector cells.

An output neuron in the retina that receives visual signals from photoreceptors via interneurons, and transmits the information to the thalamus, hypothalamus, and superior colliculus of the brain through the optic nerve.

Long-lived antigen-specific T-lymphocytes, which express CD45RO, L-selectin and CCR7. Upon subsequent exposure to their target antigen, these cells rapidly proliferate and differentiate into effector cells.

An orally available inhibitor of lysine-specific demethylase 1 (LSD1), with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon administration, INCB059872 binds to and inhibits LSD1, a demethylase that suppresses the expression of target genes by converting the di- and mono-methylated forms of lysine at position 4 of histone H3 (H3K4) to mono- and unmethylated H3K4, respectively, through amine oxidation. LSD1 inhibition enhances H3K4 methylation and increases the expression of tumor-suppressor genes. In addition, LSD1 demethylates mono- or di-methylated H3K9 which increases gene expression of tumor promoting genes; inhibition of LSD1 promotes H3K9 methylation and decreases transcription of these genes. Altogether, this may lead to an inhibition of cell growth in LSD1-overexpressing tumor cells. LSD1, an enzyme belonging to the flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD)-dependent amine oxidase family, is overexpressed in certain tumor cells and plays a key role in the regulation of gene expression and in tumor cell growth and survival.
This gene is involved in both DNA binding and nucleosome formation.

Human H1-1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 6p21.3 and is approximately 1 kb in length. This allele, which encodes histone H1.1 protein, plays a role in the formation of nucleosomes and higher-order chromatin structures.
Histone H1.1 (215 aa, ~22 kDa) is encoded by the human H1-1 gene. This protein is involved in both DNA binding and chromatin compaction into higher order structures.
The normal pattern of blood flow towards the liver through the portal vein.

Fatty acids belonging to a group of specialized pro-resolving mediators (SPM) that are either endogenously-derived from the fatty acid docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) or chemically synthesized, with potential anti-inflammatory and protective activities. Protectins promote the resolution of inflammatory responses in various tissues and may prevent tissue damage.

Dihydroxy or trihydroxy polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) belonging to a group of specialized pro-resolving mediators (SPM) that are either endogenously-derived from polyunsaturated omega-3 fatty acids or chemically synthesized, with potential anti-inflammatory and protective activities. Resolvins may promote the resolution of inflammatory responses by interacting with specific G protein-coupled receptors on inflammatory cells in various tissues and may prevent tissue damage.

label.value: Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale Revised

value.value: A self-report screening test for depression and depressive disorder measuring symptoms defined by the American Psychiatric Association Diagnostic and Statistical Manual (DSM-V) for a major depressive episode.
A neuron that sends impulses from the central nervous system to skeletal muscles, glands, and visceral organs.
A question about whether an individual's appetite is or was poor.

label.value: Could not Shake Off the Blues

value.value: A question about whether an individual could or could not shake off the blues.
A question about whether nothing makes or made an individual happy.
This gene plays a role in transcription coactivation.

Human CITED2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 6q23.3 and is approximately 3 kb in length. This allele, which encodes Cbp/p300-interacting transactivator 2 protein, is involved in transcriptional coactivation. Mutation of the gene is associated with cardiac septal defects.
Cbp/p300-interacting transactivator 2 (270 aa, ~28 kDa) is encoded by the human CITED2 gene. This protein plays a role in the positive regulation of gene expression.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt like a bad person.
A question about whether an individual loses or lost interest in their usual activities.
A question about whether an individual sleeps or slept much more than usual.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt like they are moving too slowly.
An efferent neuron that sends impulses from the central nervous system to skeletal muscles.
A question about whether an individual feels or felt fidgety.
A question about whether an individual wishes or wished they were dead.
A question about whether an individual wants or wanted to hurt themself.
A question about whether an individual is or was tired all the time.
A question about whether an individual does not like themself.

label.value: Lost a Lot of Weight Without Trying

value.value: A question about whether an individual lost a lot of weight without trying to.

label.value: Have a Lot of Trouble Getting to Sleep

value.value: A question about whether an individual has or had a lot of trouble getting to sleep.

label.value: Could Not Focus on Important Things

value.value: A question about whether an individual could or could not focus on the important things.
A response indicating that something happens or happened on one or two days.
A non-invasive serous carcinoma arising from the fallopian tube.
A motor neuron that is located in one of the ventral horns of the spinal cord and innervates skeletal muscles of the trunk or head.
A response indicating that something happens or happened on three or four days.
A response indicating that something happens or happened between five and seven days.
A response indicating that something happens or happened nearly every day for two weeks.
